-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Matthew — Part 2 (Chapters 7–12)
-- 3 difficulties × 6 chapters = 96 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 18
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 30
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 48
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 7–9 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 7 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say about judging other people?', 'Judge not, that ye be not judged', 'Always judge everyone around you', 'Only judge people you do not like', 'Judging others is always fun', 'a', 'Matthew 7:1 — "Judge not, that ye be not judged."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say about asking God for things?', 'Ask, and it shall be given you; seek, and ye shall find; knock, and it shall be opened unto you', 'Do not bother God with your requests', 'Only ask for money', 'Only grown-ups can ask God for things', 'a', 'Matthew 7:7 — "Ask, and it shall be given you; seek, and ye shall find; knock, and it shall be opened unto you."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 3, 'In Jesus'' story, what happened to the house built on the rock when the storm came?', 'It did not fall because it was founded upon a rock', 'It was washed away by the rain', 'It was blown down by the wind', 'It sank into the ground', 'a', 'Matthew 7:25 — "And the rain descended, and the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat upon that house; and it fell not: for it was founded upon a rock."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 1, 'What did Jesus say about trying to remove a speck from someone else''s eye?', 'First cast out the beam out of thine own eye; and then shalt thou see clearly to cast out the mote out of thy brother''s eye', 'You should always point out others'' faults first', 'Ignore your own faults and fix others', 'It is not your business to help anyone', 'a', 'Matthew 7:5 — "Thou hypocrite, first cast out the beam out of thine own eye; and then shalt thou see clearly to cast out the mote out of thy brother''s eye."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 2, 'What golden rule did Jesus give about treating others?', 'Therefore all things whatsoever ye would that men should do to you, do ye even so to them: for this is the law and the prophets', 'Treat others the way they treat you', 'Only be kind to your friends', 'Look out for yourself first', 'a', 'Matthew 7:12 — "Therefore all things whatsoever ye would that men should do to you, do ye even so to them: for this is the law and the prophets."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 3, 'What warning did Jesus give about false prophets?', 'Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep''s clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves — ye shall know them by their fruits', 'Accept all prophets without question', 'False prophets always look evil', 'There are no false prophets', 'a', 'Matthew 7:15-16 — "Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep''s clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves. Ye shall know them by their fruits."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 4, 'What will Jesus say to those who call Him "Lord, Lord" but do not do the will of His Father?', 'I never knew you: depart from me, ye that work iniquity', 'Welcome to my kingdom', 'You have done a wonderful job', 'Come in and rest', 'a', 'Matthew 7:23 — "And then will I profess unto them, I never knew you: depart from me, ye that work iniquity."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 5, 'What is the narrow gate that Jesus described?', 'The difficult path that leads to life — few find it, while the wide gate and broad way lead to destruction', 'The entrance to the temple', 'The gate of Jerusalem', 'A secret passage in the city walls', 'a', 'Matthew 7:13-14 — "Enter ye in at the strait gate: for wide is the gate, and broad is the way, that leadeth to destruction, and many there be which go in thereat: Because strait is the gate, and narrow is the way, which leadeth unto life, and few there be that find it."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 1, 'What does "Judge not, that ye be not judged" prohibit, and what does it not prohibit?', 'It prohibits hypocritical, censorious judgment — condemning others for faults you share or worse. It does not prohibit moral discernment (v.6 "give not that which is holy unto the dogs," v.15 "beware of false prophets"), which requires evaluation. Jesus forbids self-righteous condemnation, not spiritual discernment', 'All forms of evaluation are forbidden', 'Christians must never form opinions about behaviour', 'Only ordained ministers may judge', 'a', 'Matthew 7:1-5 — The context clarifies: the beam/mote illustration (v.3-5) targets hypocrisy, not discernment. Jesus immediately commands evaluation in v.6 (dogs/swine), v.15-20 (know them by fruits), and v.21-23 (genuine vs. false disciples). The prohibition is against playing God, not thinking critically.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 2, 'How does the ask/seek/knock trilogy (7:7-11) build on the Father analogy?', 'The three verbs escalate in intensity (ask → seek → knock), and the present tense implies persistence. The argument from lesser to greater follows: if sinful human fathers give good gifts to their children, "how much more shall your Father which is in heaven give good things to them that ask him?" God''s fatherly generosity exceeds human parenting', 'The three words mean the same thing', 'This applies only to material requests', 'The Father analogy is merely decorative', 'a', 'Matthew 7:7-11 — "Ask... seek... knock" uses present imperatives = "keep asking, keep seeking, keep knocking." The climax (v.11) uses a qal wahomer (lesser-to-greater) argument: evil humans → good gifts; how much more → good Father → good things. Prayer is grounded in God''s character, not our performance.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 3, 'What does the golden rule (7:12) mean when Jesus says "this is the law and the prophets"?', 'Jesus claims that the entire ethical teaching of the Old Testament can be summarised in proactive love — treating others as you would want to be treated. This moves beyond negative formulations ("do not harm") to positive action ("do good"). It is the practical application of the love commandments (22:37-40)', 'The golden rule replaces the Ten Commandments', 'This was a common pagan saying Jesus borrowed', 'It only applies to fellow Jews', 'a', 'Matthew 7:12 — "This is the law and the prophets." Rabbi Hillel had stated the negative form ("What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbour"). Jesus'' positive formulation is more demanding: not merely avoiding harm but actively doing good. It summarises the Sermon''s ethical vision.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 4, 'What does "by their fruits ye shall know them" teach about identifying true and false spiritual leaders?', 'Character and conduct over time — not miracles, eloquence, or popularity — are the reliable indicators of authentic spiritual authority. Good trees produce good fruit naturally; rotten trees cannot produce good fruit. This test requires patience (fruit takes seasons) and discernment (examining patterns, not isolated incidents)', 'External appearances are sufficient to judge', 'One miracle proves someone is genuine', 'Fruits refers only to numerical growth', 'a', 'Matthew 7:16-20 — "Ye shall know them by their fruits." The agricultural metaphor implies: (1) time is needed (fruit develops over seasons), (2) the connection is organic (character produces conduct), (3) the test is practical (examine results, not claims). Verses 21-23 show that even supernatural ministry can mask false hearts.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 5, 'What is the shocking implication of "Lord, Lord, have we not prophesied in thy name... and in thy name done many wonderful works"?', 'People can perform genuine supernatural acts — prophecy, exorcism, miracles — in Jesus'' name yet remain unknown to Him personally. Activity for Christ is not the same as relationship with Christ. The criterion is not ministry success but doing "the will of my Father" — personal obedience and genuine faith', 'Everyone who calls Jesus "Lord" is automatically saved', 'Miracles prove a person is right with God', 'Jesus is confused about who serves Him', 'a', 'Matthew 7:22-23 — "Many will say to me in that day, Lord, Lord, have we not prophesied in thy name?... And then will I profess unto them, I never knew you." The terrifying word is "many" — not a few self-deceived individuals but many who are active in ministry yet strangers to Christ.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 6, 'How does the wise/foolish builders parable function as the conclusion of the Sermon on the Mount?', 'The parable makes the entire Sermon intensely practical — hearing Jesus'' words is not enough; only obedient action constitutes a foundation that withstands the storm of judgment. The rock is not intellectual agreement but lived obedience. This framing makes the Sermon not merely ethical teaching but a call to radical life-reorientation', 'The parable is about literal construction techniques', 'It teaches that all houses eventually fall', 'The story is unrelated to the preceding sermon', 'a', 'Matthew 7:24-27 — "Whosoever heareth these sayings of mine, and doeth them, I will liken him unto a wise man, which built his house upon a rock." Both builders hear; only one does. The difference is not knowledge but obedience. The storm tests which foundation is real.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 7, 'What does "give not that which is holy unto the dogs, neither cast ye your pearls before swine" teach about discernment?', 'Even while prohibiting censorious judgment (v.1), Jesus requires wise discrimination — some audiences will trample and attack sacred truth. This verse balances the "judge not" teaching: Christians must neither condemn hypocritically nor share indiscriminately. Holy things must be offered with wisdom, not cast about carelessly', 'Jesus is insulting certain ethnic groups', 'Christians should never share the gospel', 'This contradicts the command not to judge', 'a', 'Matthew 7:6 — The verse requires the very discernment that v.1 seems to forbid, creating a tension resolved by distinguishing censorious condemnation (forbidden) from wise evaluation (required). The gospel is precious (pearls) and sacred (holy things); it must be handled wisely, not withheld but not forced either.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 8, 'Why were the people "astonished at his doctrine" at the end of the Sermon (7:28-29)?', 'Because Jesus taught "as one having authority, and not as the scribes" — scribes always cited prior rabbinical authorities ("Rabbi X says..."), but Jesus spoke with direct, personal authority ("I say unto you"). His claim to authoritatively interpret and deepen the Law was unprecedented and implied divine authority', 'They had never heard teaching before', 'His voice was unusually loud', 'They disagreed with everything He said', 'a', 'Matthew 7:28-29 — "The people were astonished at his doctrine: For he taught them as one having authority, and not as the scribes." The scribal method was citation-based; Jesus'' method was revelatory. He did not derive authority from tradition but possessed it inherently — a claim only God can make.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 8 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say to the man with leprosy who asked to be healed?', 'I will; be thou clean — and immediately his leprosy was cleansed', 'I cannot help you right now', 'Go see a doctor first', 'Wait until tomorrow', 'a', 'Matthew 8:3 — "And Jesus put forth his hand, and touched him, saying, I will; be thou clean. And immediately his leprosy was cleansed."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus do when a great storm arose on the sea?', 'He rebuked the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm', 'He swam to shore', 'He hid inside the boat', 'He asked the disciples to row faster', 'a', 'Matthew 8:26 — "Then he arose, and rebuked the winds and the sea; and there was a great calm."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say about the Roman centurion''s faith?', 'I have not found so great faith, no, not in Israel', 'Your faith is very weak', 'You need to believe more', 'Only people in Israel have faith', 'a', 'Matthew 8:10 — "When Jesus heard it, he marvelled, and said to them that followed, Verily I say unto you, I have not found so great faith, no, not in Israel."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 1, 'What remarkable thing did the centurion say about Jesus'' authority?', 'He said Jesus only needed to speak the word and his servant would be healed — because he understood authority, having soldiers who obey his commands', 'He asked Jesus to come and stay at his house for weeks', 'He demanded Jesus prove Himself with a sign', 'He questioned whether Jesus had any real power', 'a', 'Matthew 8:8-9 — "The centurion answered and said, Lord, I am not worthy that thou shouldest come under my roof: but speak the word only, and my servant shall be healed. For I am a man under authority, having soldiers under me."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus say to the man who wanted to bury his father before following Him?', 'Follow me; and let the dead bury their dead', 'Go and bury your father first', 'Come back in a few weeks', 'Bring your father along with you', 'a', 'Matthew 8:22 — "But Jesus said unto him, Follow me; and let the dead bury their dead."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 3, 'What did the disciples say to each other after Jesus calmed the storm?', 'What manner of man is this, that even the winds and the sea obey him!', 'Jesus is just a normal teacher', 'Maybe it was just a coincidence', 'We should not sail anymore', 'a', 'Matthew 8:27 — "But the men marvelled, saying, What manner of man is this, that even the winds and the sea obey him!"'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 4, 'What happened when Jesus healed the two demon-possessed men in the country of the Gergesenes?', 'The demons went into a herd of swine, and the whole herd ran violently down a steep place into the sea and perished', 'The demons simply disappeared', 'The men fell asleep peacefully', 'Nothing unusual happened', 'a', 'Matthew 8:32 — "And he said unto them, Go. And when they were come out, they went into the herd of swine: and, behold, the whole herd of swine ran violently down a steep place into the sea, and perished in the waters."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 5, 'Whose mother-in-law did Jesus heal of a fever?', 'Peter''s mother-in-law — He touched her hand, the fever left her, and she arose and ministered unto them', 'John''s mother-in-law', 'James''s mother-in-law', 'Andrew''s mother-in-law', 'a', 'Matthew 8:14-15 — "And when Jesus was come into Peter''s house, he saw his wife''s mother laid, and sick of a fever. And he touched her hand, and the fever left her: and she arose, and ministered unto them."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 1, 'What is the significance of Jesus touching the leper (8:3) in the cultural context?', 'Touching a leper made a person ceremonially unclean according to Leviticus 13-14. But instead of Jesus becoming unclean, the leper becomes clean — Jesus'' purity is contagious, reversing the normal direction of contamination. This is a powerful demonstration of the kingdom''s in-breaking power over disease and ritual law', 'Touching lepers was socially acceptable', 'Jesus was unaware of the purity laws', 'The touch was accidental', 'a', 'Matthew 8:3 — "Jesus put forth his hand, and touched him." The touch is deliberate and radical. Under the old covenant, uncleanness was contagious (Haggai 2:11-13); under the new, holiness is contagious. Jesus'' touch does not contract impurity — it transmits purity.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 2, 'How does the centurion''s understanding of authority reveal a profound Christology?', 'The centurion reasons from his own experience: as a man under authority whose word commands obedience, he recognises Jesus as one whose word commands disease, distance, and demons. His faith grasps that Jesus'' authority is delegated from God and operates without physical presence — a sophisticated understanding of divine power', 'The centurion was simply being polite', 'His military background was irrelevant', 'He had no real faith in Jesus', 'a', 'Matthew 8:8-10 — The centurion''s logic: "I am a man under authority... I say to this man, Go, and he goeth." He maps his chain-of-command experience onto Jesus'' relationship with creation. Just as his word moves soldiers, Jesus'' word commands sickness. This reasoning amazed Jesus Himself.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 3, 'What does Jesus'' statement that "many shall come from the east and west, and shall sit down with Abraham" predict?', 'It predicts Gentile inclusion in the kingdom of God — people from all nations will share in Abraham''s covenant blessings, while "the children of the kingdom" (unbelieving Israel) will be cast out. A Gentile centurion''s faith triggers this revolutionary declaration about the scope of salvation', 'Only Jews will enter the kingdom', 'East and west refer to the two halves of Israel', 'Abraham will host a literal dinner party', 'a', 'Matthew 8:11-12 — "Many shall come from the east and west, and shall sit down with Abraham, and Isaac, and Jacob, in the kingdom of heaven. But the children of the kingdom shall be cast out." Provoked by a Roman''s faith, Jesus announces the universal scope of the gospel.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 4, 'How does Matthew 8:17 connect Jesus'' healing ministry to Isaiah 53?', 'Matthew quotes Isaiah 53:4 — "Himself took our infirmities, and bare our sicknesses" — applying the Suffering Servant prophecy to Jesus'' healing ministry. This connection shows that Jesus'' healings are not merely compassionate acts but part of His atoning work: He bears humanity''s brokenness in all its forms', 'Isaiah 53 has nothing to do with healing', 'Matthew misquoted Isaiah', 'The healings and the cross are unrelated', 'a', 'Matthew 8:17 — "That it might be fulfilled which was spoken by Esaias the prophet, saying, Himself took our infirmities, and bare our sicknesses." Matthew uniquely applies Isaiah 53:4 to the healing ministry (not just the cross), showing that Jesus'' entire life is an expression of the Servant''s burden-bearing.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 5, 'What does "let the dead bury their dead" mean, and why is it so radical?', 'The first "dead" refers to the spiritually dead — those without kingdom urgency. Jesus is not prohibiting filial piety but asserting that following Him takes absolute priority over even the most sacred social obligations. In Jewish culture, burying one''s father was the supreme duty; Jesus claims a higher allegiance', 'Jesus was being callous about death', 'The man''s father was not actually dead', 'This applies only to Jesus'' original disciples', 'a', 'Matthew 8:22 — "Follow me; and let the dead bury their dead." Honouring parents was the weightiest commandment (Exodus 20:12). For Jesus to supersede it is to claim an authority greater than Torah — a claim only God can make. The cost of discipleship exceeds all other obligations.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 6, 'What does Jesus'' ability to calm the storm reveal about His identity?', 'In the Old Testament, only God controls the sea (Psalm 89:9, 107:29; Job 38:8-11). By rebuking the wind and sea with a word and producing instant calm, Jesus exercises divine prerogatives over creation. The disciples'' question "What manner of man is this?" points toward the answer: He is God incarnate', 'Jesus used a natural weather pattern', 'The storm was about to end anyway', 'The disciples imagined the calm', 'a', 'Matthew 8:26-27 — Jesus "rebuked the winds and the sea" — the same language used for exorcism. Psalm 89:9: "Thou rulest the raging of the sea: when the waves thereof arise, thou stillest them." Only YHWH rules the sea; Jesus does what only God does.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 7, 'Why does Matthew group ten miracles together in chapters 8-9?', 'After presenting Jesus'' authoritative teaching (Sermon on the Mount, ch. 5-7), Matthew demonstrates Jesus'' authoritative deeds (ten miracles, ch. 8-9). Word and deed together establish Jesus'' credentials as Messiah. The miracles are arranged thematically — healings, nature miracles, exorcisms — showing comprehensive authority over disease, creation, and the spiritual realm', 'Matthew randomly collected miracle stories', 'These miracles happened on the same day', 'The grouping has no literary purpose', 'a', 'Matthew structures his Gospel in alternating blocks of discourse and narrative. Chapters 5-7 (Sermon on the Mount) present Jesus'' words; chapters 8-9 present His works. Together they answer: "Is this the Messiah?" (cf. 11:2-6, Jesus'' answer to John: "the blind receive their sight...").'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of the Gergesene townspeople asking Jesus to leave after the demons were cast out?', 'They preferred their economic livelihood (the swine herd) to the presence of the Son of God — choosing material security over spiritual liberation. The episode reveals that Jesus'' transformative power can be unwelcome when it disrupts comfortable systems, even systems built on unclean practices', 'They politely invited Him to return later', 'They were grateful for the healing', 'They did not notice what had happened', 'a', 'Matthew 8:34 — "The whole city came out to meet Jesus: and when they saw him, they besought him that he would depart out of their coasts." The loss of the swine (their economy) mattered more than the deliverance of two tormented men. Material loss trumped spiritual gain — a persistent human pattern.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 9 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say to the paralysed man before healing him?', 'Son, be of good cheer; thy sins be forgiven thee', 'Stand up and walk right now', 'You need to see a doctor', 'I cannot help you today', 'a', 'Matthew 9:2 — "And, behold, they brought to him a man sick of the palsy, lying on a bed: and Jesus seeing their faith said unto the sick of the palsy; Son, be of good cheer; thy sins be forgiven thee."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 2, 'What was Matthew doing when Jesus called him to be a disciple?', 'Sitting at the tax office collecting taxes', 'Fishing in the sea', 'Working in the temple', 'Herding sheep in the fields', 'a', 'Matthew 9:9 — "And as Jesus passed forth from thence, he saw a man, named Matthew, sitting at the receipt of custom: and he saith unto him, Follow me. And he arose, and followed him."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say when people asked why He ate with sinners?', 'They that be whole need not a physician, but they that are sick', 'I only eat with good people', 'Sinners are not welcome at my table', 'I made a mistake coming here', 'a', 'Matthew 9:12 — "But when Jesus heard that, he said unto them, They that be whole need not a physician, but they that are sick."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 1, 'Why did the scribes accuse Jesus of blasphemy when He forgave sins?', 'Because only God can forgive sins — by forgiving the paralytic''s sins, Jesus was claiming divine authority, which they considered blasphemy', 'Because forgiveness was not allowed on the Sabbath', 'Because the man had committed too many sins', 'Because Jesus was not a Levite', 'a', 'Matthew 9:3 — "And, behold, certain of the scribes said within themselves, This man blasphemeth." The scribes correctly understood the implication: forgiving sins is God''s exclusive prerogative (Isaiah 43:25; Mark 2:7). Their error was not in theology but in failing to recognise God standing before them.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 2, 'How did Jesus prove He had authority to forgive sins?', 'He healed the paralytic — saying the visible miracle (healing) proves the invisible miracle (forgiveness). "That ye may know that the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins" — then He told the man to arise and walk', 'He showed them a scroll from the temple', 'He asked God to send a sign from heaven', 'He quoted from the Law of Moses', 'a', 'Matthew 9:6 — "But that ye may know that the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins, (then saith he to the sick of the palsy,) Arise, take up thy bed, and go unto thine house."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 3, 'What did Jesus mean by "new wine into new bottles (wineskins)"?', 'The new life and teaching Jesus brings cannot be contained in the old forms and traditions — new wineskins stretch with fermenting wine, but old rigid ones burst. The gospel requires new hearts and new ways of living', 'He was giving winemaking advice', 'Old wineskins are better than new ones', 'Wine should never be stored in bottles', 'a', 'Matthew 9:17 — "Neither do men put new wine into old bottles: else the bottles break, and the wine runneth out, and the bottles perish: but they put new wine into new bottles, and both are preserved."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 4, 'What happened when the woman with a blood issue touched the hem of Jesus'' garment?', 'She was immediately healed — Jesus said "Daughter, be of good comfort; thy faith hath made thee whole"', 'Nothing happened at all', 'Jesus scolded her for touching Him', 'She had to wait several days to be healed', 'a', 'Matthew 9:20-22 — "And, behold, a woman, which was diseased with an issue of blood twelve years, came behind him, and touched the hem of his garment... But Jesus turned him about, and when he saw her, he said, Daughter, be of good comfort; thy faith hath made thee whole."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 5, 'What did Jesus say when He saw the multitudes and was moved with compassion?', 'The harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few; pray ye therefore the Lord of the harvest, that he will send forth labourers into his harvest', 'There are too many people to help', 'The people do not deserve compassion', 'Someone else should take care of them', 'a', 'Matthew 9:37-38 — "Then saith he unto his disciples, The harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few; Pray ye therefore the Lord of the harvest, that he will send forth labourers into his harvest."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 1, 'What is the logical structure of Jesus'' argument in healing the paralytic to prove His authority to forgive sins?', 'Jesus uses the visible to validate the invisible — both forgiveness and healing require divine power, but healing is publicly verifiable. If Jesus can demonstrably do the harder-to-verify act (forgive sins) through the easier-to-verify act (heal a body), His authority is established. The miracle is evidence, not the essence of His ministry', 'The healing was unrelated to the forgiveness', 'Jesus was simply showing compassion', 'The scribes were convinced by the argument', 'a', 'Matthew 9:5-6 — "Whether is easier, to say, Thy sins be forgiven thee; or to say, Arise, and walk?" Both are equally easy to say but equally impossible to do without divine power. The healing proves the forgiveness because the God who can do the visible can also do the invisible.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 2, 'What does the calling of Matthew the tax collector reveal about Jesus'' kingdom values?', 'Tax collectors were considered traitors (collaborating with Rome) and sinners (profiting from extortion). Jesus deliberately choosing a tax collector as a disciple (and Gospel author) demonstrates that the kingdom accepts those whom religious society rejects, and that no background disqualifies a person from discipleship', 'Tax collectors were respected community leaders', 'Matthew was already a follower before being called', 'Jesus chose Matthew because he was wealthy', 'a', 'Matthew 9:9 — "He saw a man, named Matthew, sitting at the receipt of custom: and he saith unto him, Follow me." Matthew''s immediate response parallels the fishermen (4:20,22). A tax booth was a place of shame; Jesus made it a place of calling.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 3, 'What does "I will have mercy, and not sacrifice" (Hosea 6:6) mean in Jesus'' response to criticism about dining with sinners?', 'Jesus quotes Hosea 6:6 to show that God prioritises compassionate engagement with sinners over ritual purity and religious performance. The Pharisees'' concern for ceremonial separateness led them to avoid the very people God wanted to reach. Mercy (hesed) is the heart of God''s character, not sacrificial religion', 'Sacrifice is no longer required at all', 'God does not want any form of worship', 'Mercy means tolerating all behaviour', 'a', 'Matthew 9:13 — "But go ye and learn what that meaneth, I will have mercy, and not sacrifice: for I am not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance." Jesus directs the Pharisees to study Hosea 6:6 — a stinging rebuke suggesting they do not understand their own Scriptures.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 4, 'What does the new wine/wineskins parable teach about the relationship between Jesus'' teaching and Judaism?', 'Jesus'' gospel is not a patch on Judaism but a fundamentally new reality that requires new forms — the old wineskins of Pharisaic practice (fasting schedules, purity regulations, temple-centred religion) cannot contain the dynamic, expanding new covenant. This is not abolition but transcendence', 'Jesus was literally discussing winemaking', 'Judaism and Christianity are identical', 'The old wineskins represent Roman culture', 'a', 'Matthew 9:16-17 — The old cloth/new garment and old wineskins/new wine parables teach that Jesus'' kingdom is not a renovation of Pharisaic religion but a new creation. The forms must match the content: new wine (gospel) demands new wineskins (new covenant community).'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 5, 'What is the significance of the woman''s twelve-year bleeding and Jairus'' daughter being twelve years old?', 'The woman had been hemorrhaging for the entire lifetime of the girl — twelve years. One was slowly dying (the woman), the other was suddenly dead (the girl). Jesus'' power extends over both chronic suffering and acute death, and both are healed/raised by faith and His word/touch. The number twelve also echoes Israel''s twelve tribes', 'The number twelve is coincidental', 'Matthew invented the connection', 'Twelve was simply a round number', 'a', 'Matthew 9:18-26 — The intercalation (sandwich) of these two stories is deliberate. The hemorrhaging woman was ceremonially unclean for twelve years; Jairus'' twelve-year-old daughter had just died. Both represent extremities of human need: perpetual impurity and death itself.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 6, 'What does the title "Son of David" used by the two blind men (9:27) signify?', 'It is a messianic title — the blind men recognise Jesus as the promised descendant of David who would restore Israel and heal the afflicted (Isaiah 35:5 "the eyes of the blind shall be opened"). Their physical blindness contrasts with their spiritual sight — they see what the religious leaders miss', 'Son of David was a common greeting', 'It referred to any descendant of David', 'The blind men were confused about Jesus'' identity', 'a', 'Matthew 9:27 — "Two blind men followed him, crying, and saying, Thou Son of David, have mercy on us." "Son of David" was a loaded messianic title (cf. 2 Samuel 7:12-16, Isaiah 11:1). The irony: blind men see Jesus'' true identity while sighted Pharisees remain spiritually blind.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 7, 'What does "the harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few" reveal about Jesus'' view of the world?', 'Jesus sees the multitudes not as a problem but as a harvest — ripe, ready, and abundant. The bottleneck is not unwilling people but insufficient workers. His compassion ("moved with compassion," v.36) drives the mission imperative. Prayer for labourers (v.38) precedes sending labourers (ch. 10), showing mission begins in prayer', 'Jesus was overwhelmed by the crowds', 'The harvest metaphor refers to agriculture', 'Only the twelve can be labourers', 'a', 'Matthew 9:36-38 — "When he saw the multitudes, he was moved with compassion on them, because they fainted, and were scattered abroad, as sheep having no shepherd." The harvest metaphor shifts from agricultural to eschatological gathering. The labourers are sent by God (v.38) in response to prayer.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 8, 'How does Jesus'' response to the Pharisees'' accusation that He casts out devils by Beelzebub''s power (9:34) set up the later confrontation in chapter 12?', 'In 9:34, the Pharisees accuse Jesus of demonic power ("He casteth out devils through the prince of the devils") — Matthew records this without an immediate rebuttal, creating narrative tension. In chapter 12, the same accusation receives a devastating response about the unpardonable sin, showing the escalating conflict between Jesus and the religious establishment', 'The accusation is never addressed', 'Jesus agreed with the Pharisees', 'Chapter 12 discusses a different topic', 'a', 'Matthew 9:34 — "But the Pharisees said, He casteth out devils through the prince of the devils." This verse foreshadows the climactic confrontation in 12:22-32, where Jesus exposes the absurdity of Satan casting out Satan and warns of blasphemy against the Holy Spirit.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 10–12 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 10 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 1, 'How many special disciples (apostles) did Jesus choose and send out?', 'Twelve', 'Seven', 'Three', 'Twenty', 'a', 'Matthew 10:1-2 — "And when he had called unto him his twelve disciples, he gave them power... Now the names of the twelve apostles are these."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say about sparrows and how much God cares for us?', 'Two sparrows are sold for a farthing, but not one of them falls to the ground without your Father knowing — so do not fear, you are of more value than many sparrows', 'God only cares about big animals', 'Sparrows are more important than people', 'God does not know about sparrows', 'a', 'Matthew 10:29,31 — "Are not two sparrows sold for a farthing? and one of them shall not fall on the ground without your Father... ye are of more value than many sparrows."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say about confessing Him before men?', 'Whosoever shall confess me before men, him will I confess also before my Father which is in heaven', 'It does not matter if you talk about Jesus', 'Keep your faith completely secret', 'Only speak about Jesus in church', 'a', 'Matthew 10:32 — "Whosoever therefore shall confess me before men, him will I confess also before my Father which is in heaven."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 1, 'What instructions did Jesus give the twelve about where to go on their first mission?', 'Go not into the way of the Gentiles, and into any city of the Samaritans enter ye not: but go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel', 'Go to every nation on earth', 'Only visit the temple in Jerusalem', 'Travel to Rome and preach there', 'a', 'Matthew 10:5-6 — "Go not into the way of the Gentiles, and into any city of the Samaritans enter ye not: But go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus warn His disciples they would be like among their enemies?', 'Sheep in the midst of wolves — so be wise as serpents and harmless as doves', 'Lions among sheep', 'Eagles in the sky', 'Fish in the sea', 'a', 'Matthew 10:16 — "Behold, I send you forth as sheep in the midst of wolves: be ye therefore wise as serpents, and harmless as doves."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 3, 'What did Jesus say about fearing people versus fearing God?', 'Fear not them which kill the body, but are not able to kill the soul: but rather fear him which is able to destroy both soul and body in hell', 'Fear everyone equally', 'Do not fear anything or anyone', 'Fear only the Romans', 'a', 'Matthew 10:28 — "And fear not them which kill the body, but are not able to kill the soul: but rather fear him which is able to destroy both soul and body in hell."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say He came to bring to the earth?', 'A sword — not peace. He said following Him would sometimes divide families, because loyalty to Christ must come before all human relationships', 'Only peace and harmony everywhere', 'A new government for Israel', 'Wealth for everyone who believes', 'a', 'Matthew 10:34-36 — "Think not that I am come to send peace on earth: I came not to send peace, but a sword. For I am come to set a man at variance against his father, and the daughter against her mother."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 5, 'What did Jesus promise about even giving a cup of cold water to a disciple?', 'Whosoever shall give a cup of cold water to one of these little ones in the name of a disciple shall in no wise lose his reward', 'Only expensive gifts count', 'Small acts of kindness do not matter', 'Only apostles deserve help', 'a', 'Matthew 10:42 — "And whosoever shall give to drink unto one of these little ones a cup of cold water only in the name of a disciple, verily I say unto you, he shall in no wise lose his reward."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 1, 'Why did Jesus initially restrict the mission to "the lost sheep of the house of Israel" (10:5-6)?', 'The restriction is strategic and temporary — salvation-historical priority demanded that Israel hear first (Romans 1:16 "to the Jew first"). Israel was God''s covenant people and the Messiah''s natural audience. This limitation is explicitly removed in the Great Commission (28:19 "all nations"), showing progressive revelation', 'Jesus did not care about Gentiles', 'The restriction was permanent', 'It was a suggestion, not a command', 'a', 'Matthew 10:5-6 — "Go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel." This temporal priority mirrors Paul''s pattern in Acts (synagogue first, then Gentiles). Jesus'' own ministry crossed ethnic boundaries (8:5-13 centurion, 15:21-28 Canaanite woman), proving the restriction was strategic, not racial.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 2, 'What does "wise as serpents and harmless as doves" mean for Christian witness?', 'Disciples need both shrewdness and innocence — serpent-wisdom means being perceptive, strategic, and aware of danger; dove-harmlessness means being pure, non-violent, and transparent. The combination prevents naivety (all dove) and cunning manipulation (all serpent). Christian mission requires both intelligence and integrity', 'Christians should be devious like serpents', 'Christians should be naive like doves', 'The saying applies only to the twelve apostles', 'a', 'Matthew 10:16 — "Wise as serpents, and harmless as doves." The serpent (Genesis 3:1) represents craftiness; the dove (Genesis 8:11) represents purity. Jesus commands the paradoxical combination: discerning enough to navigate hostility, pure enough never to compromise integrity.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 3, 'What does "the disciple is not above his master, nor the servant above his lord" establish about persecution?', 'If Jesus Himself was persecuted and called "Beelzebub," His followers should expect no better treatment — persecution is normative, not exceptional, for faithful discipleship. This reframes suffering from a sign of God''s abandonment to a mark of authentic identification with Christ', 'Disciples will always be treated better than Jesus', 'Persecution only happened in the first century', 'Jesus was never actually persecuted', 'a', 'Matthew 10:24-25 — "The disciple is not above his master... If they have called the master of the house Beelzebub, how much more shall they call them of his household?" The logic: if the world''s hostility reached the Master, it will certainly reach the servants.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 4, 'What does the hair-numbering statement ("the very hairs of your head are all numbered") teach about divine providence?', 'God''s providential care extends to the minutest details of existence — if He tracks every hair on every head and every sparrow''s fall, nothing in a disciple''s life escapes His notice or care. This exhaustive providence grounds the command "fear not" (repeated three times in vv. 26, 28, 31)', 'God only cares about major events', 'The statement is hyperbolic and not literal', 'Only apostles receive this level of care', 'a', 'Matthew 10:30-31 — "But the very hairs of your head are all numbered. Fear ye not therefore, ye are of more value than many sparrows." The argument moves from lesser to greater: God''s care for sparrows (nearly worthless, two for a farthing) guarantees His infinitely greater care for His children.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 5, 'How does Jesus'' statement about bringing "a sword" (10:34) relate to His role as Prince of Peace?', 'Jesus brings ultimate peace with God (justification), but in a fallen world, allegiance to Him inevitably creates conflict with those who reject Him. The "sword" is not Jesus'' purpose but the result of His divisive claim to absolute lordship — families divide not because Jesus intends discord but because truth divides those who accept it from those who reject it', 'Jesus advocates violence', 'This contradicts the Beatitudes', 'The sword is purely symbolic of nothing', 'a', 'Matthew 10:34-36 — "I came not to send peace, but a sword." The sword is not a weapon of aggression but a metaphor for division (cf. Micah 7:6, which Jesus quotes). His peace (John 14:27) is not the absence of conflict but reconciliation with God — which provokes conflict with the world.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 6, 'What does "He that findeth his life shall lose it: and he that loseth his life for my sake shall find it" teach about discipleship?', 'The paradox of kingdom life: self-preservation leads to spiritual death, while self-sacrifice for Christ''s sake leads to true life. Those who cling to earthly security, comfort, and safety at the cost of following Jesus lose everything that matters, while those who surrender everything for Jesus gain what can never be lost', 'Christians must seek physical death', 'This applies only to martyrs', 'The saying is a contradiction with no resolution', 'a', 'Matthew 10:39 — "He that findeth his life shall lose it: and he that loseth his life for my sake shall find it." The verb "find" (heurisko) implies actively seeking. Those who make self-preservation their goal lose their soul; those who risk everything for Christ find life — real, eternal, abundant life.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 7, 'What does "freely ye have received, freely give" (10:8) establish about the nature of ministry?', 'The grace received from Christ must flow outward without commercial transaction — the disciples received their authority, healing power, and message as gifts from Jesus, and must minister in the same spirit of generosity. This principle opposes the monetisation of spiritual power and the commercialisation of the gospel', 'Ministers should always charge fees', 'Only wealthy disciples can give freely', 'This instruction was for the twelve only', 'a', 'Matthew 10:8 — "Heal the sick, cleanse the lepers, raise the dead, cast out devils: freely ye have received, freely give." Grace-based ministry reflects grace-based salvation. The gospel cannot be sold because it was never earned. This principle challenges all forms of religious profiteering.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 8, 'How does chapter 10 function as the second of Matthew''s five great discourses?', 'Matthew structures his Gospel around five major discourses (chapters 5-7, 10, 13, 18, 23-25), each ending with "when Jesus had finished." Chapter 10 is the Mission Discourse, commissioning the twelve and establishing principles for all future Christian mission — including persecution, dependence on God, fearless witness, and the cost of discipleship', 'Matthew has no structured discourses', 'Chapter 10 is a collection of random sayings', 'There are only two discourses in Matthew', 'a', 'Matthew 10 — The five-discourse structure (chs. 5-7, 10, 13, 18, 23-25) may parallel the five books of Moses, presenting Jesus as the new Moses/Lawgiver. Chapter 10 moves from initial commission (vv.1-15) to future persecution (vv.16-25) to exhortations for fearless faith (vv.26-42).');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 11 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 11, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus tell John the Baptist''s followers to report back to John in prison?', 'The blind receive their sight, and the lame walk, the lepers are cleansed, and the deaf hear, the dead are raised up, and the poor have the gospel preached to them', 'I am building a great army', 'I am too busy to answer', 'Tell John to escape from prison', 'a', 'Matthew 11:4-5 — "Go and shew John again those things which ye do hear and see: The blind receive their sight, and the lame walk, the lepers are cleansed, and the deaf hear, the dead are raised up, and the poor have the gospel preached to them."'),
('Matthew', 11, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus invite weary people to do?', 'Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest', 'Work harder and you will feel better', 'Go to the temple and pay money', 'Ask the Pharisees for help', 'a', 'Matthew 11:28 — "Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest."'),
('Matthew', 11, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say about His yoke?', 'My yoke is easy, and my burden is light', 'My yoke is very heavy and hard', 'I do not have a yoke', 'Only strong people can carry my yoke', 'a', 'Matthew 11:30 — "For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 11, 'teens', 1, 'Why did John the Baptist send messengers to ask Jesus "Art thou he that should come?"', 'John was in prison and possibly struggling with doubt — Jesus was not overthrowing Rome or judging the wicked as John had expected the Messiah to do, so he sought reassurance', 'John did not believe in Jesus at all', 'John wanted to publicly embarrass Jesus', 'John had never heard of Jesus before', 'a', 'Matthew 11:2-3 — "Now when John had heard in the prison the works of Christ, he sent two of his disciples, And said unto him, Art thou he that should come, or do we look for another?" John had preached fiery judgment (3:10-12); Jesus was showing mercy. The disconnect prompted his question.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus say about John the Baptist''s importance?', 'Among them that are born of women there hath not risen a greater than John the Baptist — yet he that is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he', 'John was a minor prophet of little importance', 'John was equal to all other prophets', 'John was greater than Jesus', 'a', 'Matthew 11:11 — "Verily I say unto you, Among them that are born of women there hath not risen a greater than John the Baptist: notwithstanding he that is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he."'),
('Matthew', 11, 'teens', 3, 'Why did Jesus criticise the cities of Chorazin, Bethsaida, and Capernaum?', 'Because most of His mighty works had been done there yet they did not repent — He said it would be more tolerable for Tyre, Sidon, and Sodom on the day of judgment', 'Because they worshipped Roman gods', 'Because they refused to pay taxes', 'Because they were too far from Jerusalem', 'a', 'Matthew 11:20-24 — "Then began he to upbraid the cities wherein most of his mighty works were done, because they repented not... it shall be more tolerable for the land of Sodom in the day of judgment, than for thee."'),
('Matthew', 11, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say God had hidden from the wise and revealed to babes?', 'The things of the kingdom — the truths of the gospel. God reveals His salvation to the humble and childlike rather than to the intellectually proud', 'A secret treasure map', 'A new set of commandments', 'The location of the temple', 'a', 'Matthew 11:25 — "I thank thee, O Father, Lord of heaven and earth, because thou hast hid these things from the wise and prudent, and hast revealed them unto babes."'),
('Matthew', 11, 'teens', 5, 'What does Jesus promise those who take His yoke upon them?', 'They will find rest for their souls — because His yoke is easy and His burden is light, and He is meek and lowly in heart', 'They will become famous and powerful', 'They will never have any problems', 'They will become wealthy', 'a', 'Matthew 11:29-30 — "Take my yoke upon you, and learn of me; for I am meek and lowly in heart: and ye shall find rest unto your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 1, 'How does Jesus'' answer to John''s question (11:4-6) confirm His messiahship without directly saying "yes"?', 'Jesus points to Isaiah 35:5-6 and 61:1 being fulfilled — the blind see, lame walk, lepers are cleansed, deaf hear, dead are raised, poor hear the gospel. By listing these specific miracles, He lets Scripture identify Him as the Messiah without making a direct political claim that could be misused', 'Jesus was avoiding the question', 'Jesus did not think He was the Messiah', 'The miracles were coincidental', 'a', 'Matthew 11:4-5 — Jesus catalogues His works using Isaiah''s messianic checklist (Isaiah 35:5-6, 61:1). The final beatitude ("blessed is he, whosoever shall not be offended in me," v.6) gently corrects John: the Messiah''s programme includes mercy before judgment. Trust the evidence.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 2, 'What does "he that is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than John" mean?', 'It refers to redemptive-historical position, not personal merit — John was the greatest under the old covenant as the forerunner, but even the least person living under the new covenant (post-cross, post-resurrection, post-Pentecost) has greater spiritual privilege: the indwelling Spirit, completed revelation, and accomplished atonement', 'John was morally inferior to all Christians', 'The least in the kingdom is literally greater in every way', 'Jesus was criticising John', 'a', 'Matthew 11:11 — "He that is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he." Greater in privilege, not in character. John stood at the threshold looking in; new covenant believers live inside the reality John pointed toward. The distinction is epochal, not personal.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 3, 'What does "the kingdom of heaven suffereth violence, and the violent take it by force" (11:12) mean?', 'This difficult saying most likely means the kingdom of heaven is being forcefully advanced (through Jesus'' ministry) and determined people lay hold of it with intense spiritual earnestness — or alternatively, violent people (like Herod, who imprisoned John) attack the kingdom. Both interpretations acknowledge the kingdom''s controversial, contested nature', 'Christians should use physical violence', 'The kingdom is being conquered by enemies', 'Only soldiers can enter the kingdom', 'a', 'Matthew 11:12 — "The kingdom of heaven suffereth violence, and the violent take it by force." The Greek allows both "the kingdom is violently attacked" and "the kingdom is forcefully entered." In context (John imprisoned, Jesus'' ministry opposed), both meanings are present: the kingdom provokes opposition and demands urgency.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 4, 'What does Jesus'' "woe" pronouncements on Galilean cities teach about degrees of judgment?', 'Greater revelation brings greater accountability — Chorazin, Bethsaida, and Capernaum witnessed more miracles than Tyre, Sidon, and Sodom, so their rejection is more culpable. "More tolerable" implies degrees of judgment based on the light received. Privilege without response increases condemnation', 'All judgment is exactly the same', 'Tyre and Sidon were righteous cities', 'Jesus was being unfair to these cities', 'a', 'Matthew 11:20-24 — "More tolerable for Tyre and Sidon... for the land of Sodom." The principle: judgment is proportional to revelation. Sodom never saw Jesus'' miracles; Capernaum did. Greater light refused = greater condemnation. This principle appears throughout Scripture (Luke 12:48, Hebrews 10:29).'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 5, 'What does the statement "All things are delivered unto me of my Father" (11:27) claim about Jesus?', 'It is one of the highest Christological claims in the Synoptic Gospels — Jesus claims universal authority delegated by the Father, exclusive mutual knowledge between Father and Son, and sole mediatorial power to reveal the Father. This "Johannine thunderbolt" sounds like John''s Gospel dropped into Matthew''s narrative', 'Jesus was speaking metaphorically about general knowledge', 'This claim was added by later editors', 'It refers only to teaching authority', 'a', 'Matthew 11:27 — "All things are delivered unto me of my Father: and no man knoweth the Son, but the Father; neither knoweth any man the Father, save the Son, and he to whomsoever the Son will reveal him." The exclusive mutual knowledge between Father and Son implies shared divine nature.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 6, 'How does "Come unto me, all ye that labour and are heavy laden" contrast with the Pharisaic system?', 'The Pharisees burdened people with endless rules and interpretations (23:4 "heavy burdens and grievous to be borne"). Jesus offers rest instead of religious exhaustion. His "yoke" (a rabbinic term for one''s teaching and interpretation of the Law) is easy because it flows from relationship with a meek and lowly Master, not from legalistic performance', 'The Pharisees also offered rest', 'Jesus was promoting laziness', 'This invitation was only for the twelve disciples', 'a', 'Matthew 11:28-30 — "Come unto me... I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you." A rabbi''s "yoke" was his interpretation of Torah. Jesus'' yoke replaces the crushing burden of Pharisaic legalism with grace-empowered obedience flowing from a relationship with Christ Himself.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 7, 'What does "no man knoweth the Son, but the Father" imply about Jesus'' nature?', 'The claim that only God the Father can fully know the Son implies the Son shares the divine nature — only infinite knowledge can comprehend an infinite being. This reciprocal exclusivity (only the Father knows the Son; only the Son knows the Father) places Jesus in a unique ontological category shared only with God', 'Jesus was difficult to understand personally', 'The disciples knew Jesus fully', 'This is about secret information, not nature', 'a', 'Matthew 11:27 — "No man knoweth the Son, but the Father; neither knoweth any man the Father, save the Son." Comprehension of the Son requires the Father''s infinite knowledge, implying the Son is infinite. The parallel structure places Father and Son on the same level of being.'),
('Matthew', 11, 'adults', 8, 'What does the comparison of "this generation" to children in the marketplace (11:16-19) diagnose about spiritual obstinacy?', 'Jesus compares His critics to petulant children who refuse to play any game — they rejected John''s asceticism ("he hath a devil") and Jesus'' sociability ("a man gluttonous and a winebibber"). The problem is not the messenger''s style but the audience''s hardness. "Wisdom is justified of her children" means the results of both ministries vindicate God''s approach', 'Jesus was praising the generation', 'Only children were guilty of this behaviour', 'The parable is about literal marketplace games', 'a', 'Matthew 11:16-19 — "We have piped unto you, and ye have not danced; we have mourned unto you, and ye have not lamented." Neither the ascetic (John) nor the social (Jesus) approach satisfied the critics. Their complaint was not about method but about message: repentance and faith.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 12 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 12, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say was lawful to do on the Sabbath?', 'It is lawful to do well on the sabbath days — He healed a man''s withered hand on the Sabbath', 'Nothing at all should be done on the Sabbath', 'Only cooking is allowed on the Sabbath', 'You must stay in bed all day', 'a', 'Matthew 12:12 — "Wherefore it is lawful to do well on the sabbath days."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say people would give account for on the day of judgment?', 'Every idle word that men shall speak', 'Only the biggest sins they committed', 'Only the things they did, not what they said', 'Only the sins they remembered', 'a', 'Matthew 12:36 — "But I say unto you, That every idle word that men shall speak, they shall give account thereof in the day of judgment."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'kids', 3, 'What sign did Jesus say He would give the scribes and Pharisees?', 'The sign of the prophet Jonas — as Jonas was three days and three nights in the whale''s belly, so Jesus would be three days and nights in the heart of the earth', 'A sign of fire from heaven', 'A sign of water from the rock', 'A sign of manna from the sky', 'a', 'Matthew 12:39-40 — "An evil and adulterous generation seeketh after a sign; and there shall no sign be given to it, but the sign of the prophet Jonas: For as Jonas was three days and three nights in the whale''s belly; so shall the Son of man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 12, 'teens', 1, 'How did Jesus defend His disciples when the Pharisees accused them of breaking the Sabbath by picking grain?', 'He cited David eating the shewbread (1 Samuel 21) and priests working in the temple on the Sabbath — and declared "the Son of man is Lord even of the sabbath day"', 'He apologised to the Pharisees', 'He punished the disciples for picking grain', 'He agreed with the Pharisees completely', 'a', 'Matthew 12:3-8 — "Have ye not read what David did... how he entered into the house of God, and did eat the shewbread? ...the Son of man is Lord even of the sabbath day."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus say about a kingdom divided against itself?', 'Every kingdom divided against itself is brought to desolation; and every city or house divided against itself shall not stand', 'Divided kingdoms are stronger', 'Division does not affect kingdoms', 'Only human kingdoms can be divided', 'a', 'Matthew 12:25 — "Every kingdom divided against itself is brought to desolation; and every city or house divided against itself shall not stand."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'teens', 3, 'What is the one sin Jesus said will not be forgiven?', 'Blasphemy against the Holy Ghost — speaking against the Holy Ghost shall not be forgiven, neither in this world nor the next', 'Telling a small lie', 'Missing a day of prayer', 'Working on the Sabbath', 'a', 'Matthew 12:31-32 — "All manner of sin and blasphemy shall be forgiven unto men: but the blasphemy against the Holy Ghost shall not be forgiven unto men."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say about a tree and its fruit?', 'Either make the tree good, and his fruit good; or else make the tree corrupt, and his fruit corrupt: for the tree is known by his fruit', 'Bad trees can produce good fruit', 'Trees have nothing to do with people', 'All trees produce the same fruit', 'a', 'Matthew 12:33 — "Either make the tree good, and his fruit good; or else make the tree corrupt, and his fruit corrupt: for the tree is known by his fruit."'),
('Matthew', 12, 'teens', 5, 'Who did Jesus say are His mother and brothers?', 'Whosoever shall do the will of my Father which is in heaven, the same is my brother, and sister, and mother', 'Only His biological family members', 'Only the twelve disciples', 'Only people from Nazareth', 'a', 'Matthew 12:50 — "For whosoever shall do the will of my Father which is in heaven, the same is my brother, and sister, and mother."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 1, 'How do Jesus'' Sabbath controversies (12:1-14) redefine the relationship between law and mercy?', 'Jesus establishes the principle "I will have mercy, and not sacrifice" (quoting Hosea 6:6 again, cf. 9:13) — the Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath. He claims lordship over the Sabbath (v.8), placing Himself above the institution. Human need and divine mercy take precedence over rigid ceremonial observance', 'Jesus abolished the Sabbath entirely', 'The Pharisees were correct in every detail', 'Sabbath rules were never important', 'a', 'Matthew 12:7-8 — "If ye had known what this meaneth, I will have mercy, and not sacrifice, ye would not have condemned the guiltless. For the Son of man is Lord even of the sabbath day." Jesus does not reject Sabbath but recentres it on its purpose: blessing humanity, not burdening it.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 2, 'What exactly is "blasphemy against the Holy Ghost" and why is it unforgivable?', 'In context, it is the deliberate, persistent attribution of the Holy Spirit''s work to Satan — seeing Christ''s miracles performed by the Spirit and calling them demonic. It is unforgivable not because God''s grace has a limit but because this sin, by its nature, permanently rejects the very agent of conviction and repentance (the Spirit), making forgiveness impossible since the person refuses the only means of salvation', 'Any sin committed more than once', 'Doubting God''s existence temporarily', 'Using God''s name carelessly', 'a', 'Matthew 12:31-32 — The context is crucial: the Pharisees attributed Jesus'' Spirit-empowered exorcism to Beelzebub (v.24). This is not a momentary doubt but a settled, eyes-open rejection of the Spirit''s testimony to Christ. The sin is unforgivable because it refuses the only remedy.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 3, 'How does the sign of Jonah typologically prefigure Jesus'' death and resurrection?', 'As Jonah was three days and nights in the great fish before emerging alive, so Jesus would be three days in the earth before rising — the only sign Jesus offers a sign-seeking generation is His own death and resurrection. Jonah''s emergence brought repentance to Nineveh; Jesus'' resurrection brings salvation to the world', 'Jonah and Jesus have no connection', 'The sign refers to a literal whale appearing', 'Three days is an approximate number with no significance', 'a', 'Matthew 12:40 — "As Jonas was three days and three nights in the whale''s belly; so shall the Son of man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth." The typology: Jonah''s "death" and "resurrection" from the fish points to Christ''s actual death and bodily resurrection.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 4, 'What does the parable of the returning unclean spirit (12:43-45) warn about?', 'Moral reformation without spiritual regeneration is dangerous — merely cleaning up behaviour (the empty, swept house) without being filled with God''s Spirit invites worse spiritual bondage. The last state becomes worse than the first because emptiness invites occupation. The application is to "this wicked generation" that rejects Christ', 'Demons cannot return once expelled', 'Houses should be kept unswept', 'This only applies to demon-possessed individuals', 'a', 'Matthew 12:43-45 — "The last state of that man is worse than the first. Even so shall it be also unto this wicked generation." Self-improvement without Spirit-filling creates a spiritual vacuum. The parable warns Israel: rejecting the Messiah after hearing His message leaves them worse off than before.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 5, 'What does Jesus'' claim to be "greater than the temple" (12:6) and "greater than Jonas" and "greater than Solomon" (12:41-42) assert?', 'These "greater than" statements make extraordinary claims: Jesus is greater than Israel''s holiest place (temple — where God dwelt), greatest prophet (Jonah — who brought Nineveh to repentance), and wisest king (Solomon — whose wisdom drew the queen of Sheba). The cumulative effect is a claim to divine supremacy over all institutions and persons in Israel''s history', 'Jesus was being modest', 'He was only greater in age', 'These claims were later additions', 'a', 'Matthew 12:6,41,42 — "One greater than the temple is here... greater than Jonas... greater than Solomon." Temple = God''s dwelling; Jesus is the true temple (John 2:19-21). Jonah = prophet; Jesus is the ultimate prophet. Solomon = wise king; Jesus is the wisdom of God (1 Corinthians 1:24).'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 6, 'How does Jesus'' redefinition of family (12:46-50) reshape the concept of community?', 'Jesus creates a new family defined not by blood but by obedience to God''s will — spiritual kinship supersedes biological kinship. This is not a rejection of His physical family but a declaration that the kingdom creates a new community where doing the Father''s will makes one a brother, sister, and mother of Jesus Himself', 'Jesus was disowning His family', 'Only the twelve apostles are His family', 'Biological family is unimportant to God', 'a', 'Matthew 12:49-50 — "He stretched forth his hand toward his disciples, and said, Behold my mother and my brethren! For whosoever shall do the will of my Father." The gesture (stretching out His hand) includes all disciples, creating the nucleus of a new community defined by shared obedience rather than shared DNA.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 7, 'What does "out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaketh" (12:34) teach about the relationship between speech and character?', 'Words are diagnostic — they reveal the true condition of the heart, just as fruit reveals the nature of a tree (v.33). A "good treasure" of the heart produces good speech; an "evil treasure" produces evil speech. This is why every "idle word" (argon — careless, unguarded) will be judged: unguarded words are the most revealing of character', 'Words have no connection to the heart', 'Only written words matter', 'Idle words are always forgiven', 'a', 'Matthew 12:34-37 — "For out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaketh... By thy words thou shalt be justified, and by thy words thou shalt be condemned." Words are not arbitrary sounds but the overflow of character. Careless speech is the truest window into the soul.'),
('Matthew', 12, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of Jesus quoting Isaiah 42:1-4 (the Servant Song) in Matthew 12:18-21?', 'Matthew applies Isaiah''s first Servant Song to Jesus to explain why He withdraws and heals quietly (v.15-16) rather than seeking confrontation — the Servant will not quarrel or cry out, will not break a bruised reed, and will bring forth judgment unto victory. Gentile hope is highlighted: "in his name shall the Gentiles trust"', 'Isaiah 42 has no messianic meaning', 'Jesus was a violent revolutionary', 'Matthew invented the quotation', 'a', 'Matthew 12:18-21 — "He shall not strive, nor cry; neither shall any man hear his voice in the streets. A bruised reed shall he not break." Isaiah''s Servant is gentle with the weak, quiet in method, and universal in scope. Jesus'' withdrawal from conflict (v.15) fulfils this portrait of patient, compassionate messiahship.');
